\subsection*{2.6. Factors that Affect the Oxygen Equilibrium Curve}

The oxygen equilibrium properties of haemoglobin are altered by changes in concentration of protons (Wyman, 1939) and salts (Antonini et al., 1962), in particular by 2,3-diphosphoglycerate (DPG) (Benesch and Benesch, 1967; Chanutin and Curnish, 1967). The oxygen equilibrium is also different for haemoglobins with mutations or chemical modifications. The relationship between the changes in oxygen binding properties and free energy differences is discussed below, the treatment being based on that of Wyman (1948, 1964, 1965, 1967) and being similar to that of Szabo and Karplus (1975a, b).

\subsection*{2.6.1. Abnormal haemoglobins}

Consider an abnormal haemoglobin represented by the energy diagram in Fig. 4b. Suppose that the abnormality alters the intrinsic affinity of a free subunit, so that its median ligand activity is $A_{s}^{*}$, and the association constants of the oxy and deoxy forms of the tetramer are $\mathrm{KS}_{4}^{*}$ and $\mathrm{KS}_{6}^{*}$. Then from eq. (2.15)
$$\ln p_{m}^{*}=\ln p_{s}^{*}+\frac{1}{4} \ln \frac{K S_{0}^{*}}{K S_{4}^{*}} .$$

The difference in $\log p_{m}$ between an abnormal and normal haemoglobin, $\Delta \log p_{m}$, is therefore given by
$$\Delta \log p_{m}=\Delta \log p_{s}+\frac{1}{4}\left(\log \frac{K S_{0}}{K S_{4}}-\log \frac{K S_{\%}^{*}}{K S_{4}^{*}}\right) .$$
$\Delta \log p_{m}$ is made up of a term due to the difference in intrinsic affinity of the free subunit
and a term due to the altered association constants of the subunits to tetramers between the two systems.
$$\mathrm{RT}\left(\ln \frac{K S_{0}}{K S_{4}}-\ln \frac{K S_{6}^{*}}{K S_{4}^{*}}\right)$$
is the difference of two free energy differences, $\mathrm{RT} \ln K S_{0} / K S_{4}$ being the difference between the free energy of deoxy subunits in a deoxy tetramer and the free energy of oxy subunits in an oxy tetramer, $\mathrm{RT} \ln K S_{0}^{*} / K S_{4}^{*}$ being the corresponding difference for the abnormal haemoglobin. Thus the expression for $\Delta \log p_{m}$ between an abnormal and normal haemoglobin involves terms due to the intrinsic affinity of the free subunits and terms associated with the stability of these subunits in fully liganded and in deoxy tetramers. It is quite independent of the stability of the intermediate states. From Fig. $4 a, b$ it can be seen that the stability changes between the normal and abnormal systems result in different stabilities for the deoxy tetramers and different stabilities for the oxy tetramers. The two halves of the diagram have been drawn with the unliganded free subunits at arbitrarily fixed energy levels since it is only the difference between these stability differences that is meaningful. The three-dimensional structures of normal and abnormal haemoglobins may show why the stability of the abnormal deoxy structure is altered relative to the normal deoxy structure to a different extent from that of the abnormal oxy structure relative to the normal oxy structure. This would give a structural understanding of the difference in $p_{m}$.

The effect on co-operativity, as seen in altered values of $n$ and $\Delta F_{I}$, will depend on changes in the stability of the partially liganded states which are not observable by X-ray techniques.

