The condition for linearity of release of $X$ with oxygen binding.
$$\Delta X_{i}=-\frac{d \log A_{i x}^{\prime}}{d \log x} \quad \text { from eq.(2.27). }$$

Release of $X$ is the same at all stages of oxygen binding if the Adair constants all depend on the concentration of $X$ in the same way, i.e. they have the same concentration dependent term as a multiplier. As just discussed above, this is the condition for invariance of shape of the equilibrium curves as the concentration of $X$ varies. Linearity of release of $X$ and invariance of shape of the equilibrium curves with change in concentration of $X$ are therefore thermodynamic consequences of each other, or in Wyman's terminology they are linked.

One particularly simple example in which release of $X$ is exactly linear with oxygenation is the case when each subunit within the tetramer releases ligand only due to changes in tertiary structure depending on its own state of oxygenation, independently of the state of oxygenation of the other subunits. Then each Adair constant has a multiplying term
$$\left(\frac{1+Q_{s 1} x}{1+Q_{s 0} x}\right)$$
where $Q_{s 0}$ is the binding constant of $X$ to the deoxy subunit and $Q_{s 1}$ the binding constant to the oxy subunit. The release of $X$ at each stage of oxygenation is
