\section*{3. THE STRUCTURE OF HAEMOGLOBIN}

The three-dimensional structure of haemoglobin has been studied by the methods of X-ray crystallography. From low resolution studies, the haemoglobin molecule was shown to comprise two pairs of identical subunits, the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains (Cullis et al., 1962). The structure of each subunit is similar to that of the monomeric respiratory protein myoglobin (Kendrew et al., 1961). The four subunits are arranged tetrahedrally and the structure is such that the four haem groups, the binding sites for oxygen, are far apart, each in a separate pocket on the surface of the molecule. The arrangement of the four subunits in the haemoglobin tetramer is different in deoxygenated and liganded haemoglobin (Muirhead and Perutz, 1963), explaining Haurowitz's observation (1938) that crystals of deoxyhaemoglobin dissolve on exposure to air and that oxyhaemoglobin crystals with a different morphology precipitate from the solution. Electron density maps have now been made at high resolution $(\sim 2.8 \AA)$ for horse methaemoglobin (i.e. haemoglobin with the iron atoms in the ferric state with water molecules as haem ligands) and for horse and human deoxyhaemoglobin (Perutz et al., 1968a, 1968b; Bolton and Perutz, 1970; Muirhead and Greer, 1970; Arnone et al., 1975). With the aid
of the amino acid sequences of the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-polypeptide chains, which have been determined for both horse and human haemoglobin (see Dayhoff, 1973) atomic models of the structures have been built from the electron density maps. The accuracy of the latest models is such that from the better determined regions of the maps, for example the polypeptide backbone in helical regions and the internal side chains, the atoms, except for hydrogens, can be positioned to within $0.5 \AA$. The surface side chains and some parts of the structure that are ill defined in the maps are positioned less well (McLachlan and Fermi, 1975). The following sections will discuss briefly those aspects of the structures of deoxy and liganded haemoglobin that are important in the present understanding of haemoglobin function.

