The differences of tertiary structure between deoxy-erythrocruorin and carbonmonoxy-erythrocruorin can be taken as an indication of the tertiary structure changes that would be induced by the combination of an isolated deoxy subunit of haemoglobin with a ligand that changes the iron to a low spin state. The study of erythrocruorin indicates that very little tertiary structure change occurs when an isolated deoxy subunit combines with a ligand that leaves the iron atom in a high spin state.

Spectral differences associated with different ligands at the haem. Changes in the electronic absorption spectrum from the haem groups occur on ligation of the free subunits and myoglobin. Deoxy chains have an absorption spectrum characterized by a single broad and asymmetrical band in the visible region and a band known as the Soret band in the near ultraviolet. Also in the ultraviolet and the near-infrared region the absorption spectrum shows specific features. On oxygenation or combination with other ligands there are changes in the absorption spectrum in both the visible and Soret bands. For details of the deoxy spectra and the changes with different ligands the reader is referred to the recent book by van Assendelft (1970).

\subsection*{3.3. The Structure of Liganded Haemoglobin}

The arrangement of the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-subunits in liganded haemoglobin is illustrated in Fig. 1 which shows the model of the structure built from the low resolution electron density map (Cullis et al., 1962). The structure of aquomethaemoglobin has now been studied to $2.8 \AA$ resolution and an atomic model built (Perutz et al., 1968a, b). The tertiary structures of subunits in the haemoglobin tetramer are very similar to the tertiary structure of myoglobin, although both the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains have some differences in detail. The iron atom is estimated to be out of the mean plane of the porphyrin ring towards the proximal histidine by $0.1 \AA$ in the $\alpha$-chains and by $0.2 \AA$ in the $\beta$-chains, whilst the porphyrin ring itself is slightly bent. The distance of the imidazole nitrogen of the haem-linked histidine from the mean porphyrin plane is $2.4 \AA$ in the $\alpha$-chains and $2.5 \AA$ in the $\beta$-chains (Heidner et al., 1975).

Contacts between the subunits are of four possible kinds, $\alpha_{1} \alpha_{2}, \beta_{1} \beta_{2}, \alpha_{1} \beta_{1}, \alpha_{1} \beta_{2}$. No contacts between like chains are visible in the electron density map, but there may possibly be a few polar contacts involving the terminal residues of the subunits (see Table 7). Both the carboxyl terminal and amino terminal residues of the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains appear to be free and delocalized in the structure. Also the penultimate residues at the C-termini, tyrosines HC2(140) $\alpha$ and HC2(145) $\beta$, appear only partially localized since the electron density corresponding to them is very low.

The contact $\alpha_{1} \beta_{1}$ is the most extensive intersubunit contact in the tetramer, with 34 residues in contact involving 110 atoms coming within a distance of $4 \AA$ of each other. The majority of these interactions are non-polar with a few probable hydrogen bonds. The contact $\alpha_{1} \beta_{2}$ is made up of 19 residues contributing about 80 atoms within a
distance of $4 \AA$ of each other. Again, most of the interactions are non-polar but there is one clear hydrogen bond between aspartate $\mathrm{G} 1(94) \alpha$ and asparagine $\mathrm{G} 4(102) \beta$. Table 6a lists the interatomic contacts between $\alpha_{1}$ and $\beta_{2}$.

Comparison of the structure of carbonmonoxyhaemoglobin with that of aquomethaemoglobin has shown that the arrangement of the subunits in the tetramer is the same although there are small differences in the tertiary structure of the subunits in the region of the haem groups and at the C-termini of the chains (Heidner et al., 1975). The position of the iron atom in the low spin ferrous derivative is closer to the plane of the porphyrin ring, and there is a change in position of the distal histidine. Associated with the difference in position of the iron atom closer to the plane of the haem there appeared to be a rotation of the F helix such that in the $\beta$-chains the sulphydryl group of cysteine $\mathrm{F9}(93) \beta$ was moved from an exposed position in methaemoglobin to a more shielded one in carbonmonoxyhaemoglobin. The -SH group moves into the pocket partially occupied by Tyr $145 \beta$ in methaemoglobin so that in carbonmonoxyhaemoglobin the penultimate tyrosine must be even more delocalized than in methaemoglobin.

