\subsection*{3.4. The Structure of Deoxyhaemoglobin and its Comparison with Liganded Haemoglobin}

There is a difference in quaternary structure, i.e. the arrangement of the four subunits in the tetramer, between liganded and deoxyhaemoglobin. The geometry of the rearrangement of the subunits was originally determined from the low resolution electron density maps of horse met and horse and human deoxyhaemoglobin (Muirhead et al., 1967; Bolton et al., 1968). In this rearrangement there is relatively little change within the $\alpha_{1} \beta_{1}$ pair of subunits, but a large movement between the $\alpha_{1} \beta_{1}$ and $\alpha_{2} \beta_{2}$ pairs of subunits. The structures of horse and human deoxyhaemoglobin have now been studied to $2.8 \AA$ and $2.5 \AA$ resolution, respectively, and atomic models have been built (Bolton and Perutz, 1970; Arnone et al., 1975; McLachlan and Fermi, 1975). The differences in tertiary structure of the subunits between liganded and deoxyhaemoglobin are small but they are significant in the region of the haem groups and the intersubunit contacts.

The haem groups in deoxyhaemoglobin are in contact with the same residues as in methaemoglobin but the details of the contacts have changed since the haem group appears to tilt slightly in the haem pocket when there is no ligand in it. The iron atom is estimated to be $0.60 \AA$ and $0.63 \AA$ out of the plane of the flat porphyrin ring towards the
proximal histidine in the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains respectively of human deoxyhaemoglobin. The distance of the imidazole nitrogen of the haem-linked histidine from the mean porphyrin plane is estimated to be $2.6 \AA$ in the $\alpha$-chains and $2.8 \AA$ in the $\beta$-chains (Fermi, 1975). The size of the haem ligand pocket is noticeably smaller in the $\beta$-chains of deoxyhaemoglobin relative to liganded $\beta$-chains, whereas the ligand pocket appears to be the same width in deoxy and met $\alpha$-chains.

Contacts between the $\alpha_{1}$ - and $\alpha_{2}$-chains are seen in deoxyhaemoglobin in contrast to liganded haemoglobin where there were none (Muirhead and Greer, 1970; Bolton and Perutz, 1970). The $\alpha$-carboxyl group of arginine $\mathrm{HC} 3(141) \alpha_{2}$ is in contact with the $\epsilon$-amino group of lysine $\mathrm{H} 10(127) \alpha_{1}$. Also the guanidinium group of $\operatorname{Arg} 141 \alpha_{2}$ forms a salt bridge with aspartate $\mathrm{H} 9(126) \alpha_{1}$. In the electron density maps of Muirhead and Greer (1970) and Bolton and Perutz (1970), the $\alpha$-amino group of valine $1 \alpha_{1}$ appeared to make a contact with the $\alpha$-carboxyl of Arg $141 \alpha_{2}$. In a later map at higher resolution (Arnone et al., 1975) Val $1 \alpha_{1}$ is too far away from the $\alpha$-carboxyl to be a contact and there may be a water molecule between the two groups. Figure 7 illustrates the arrangement of the charged groups in the region of the N -terminus of $\alpha_{1}$ and the C-terminus of $\alpha_{2}$ as determined from the latest map of human deoxyhaemoglobin. The penultimate tyrosine $\mathrm{HC} 2(140) \alpha$ is clearly defined in the deoxy structure in a pocket between the $\mathbf{F}$ and $\mathbf{H}$ helices, in contrast again to the situation in liganded haemoglobin.

