\subsection*{3.5. Conformation Differences Between Liganded and Unliganded Haemoglobin in Solution}

Many techniques have been used to study the conformation differences between liganded and unliganded haemoglobin in solution. Most of the differences detected by these methods can be interpreted in terms of the three-dimensional structures derived from crystallographic studies described above, and suggest that these structures are the same as those of liganded and unliganded haemoglobin in solution.

The difference in affinity for ligands such as protons and organic phosphates between oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin, discussed in section 2.6 in relation to the consequent effect on the oxygen affinity, is an indication of conformation differences in the vicinity of the binding sites for these ligands. The interaction of haemoglobin with protons, and organic phosphates will be discussed in detail in section 4.

The rate of reaction of the sulphydryl group of Cys F9(93)B with the reagent N-ethylmaleimide (NEM) was shown by Riggs (1961) to differ in liganded and deoxyhaemoglobin. Table 8 shows recent data on the second order rate constants for the reaction of the -SH group with $p$-mercuribenzoate (PMB) in liganded and deoxyhaemoglobins. Oxyhaemoglobin has a higher rate constant than deoxyhaemoglobin by a factor of 45. The liganded haemoglobins all have higher rates than deoxyhaemoglobin that differ from each other only by small factors.

