Conformation differences in the vicinity of $\beta 93$ have also been detected by electron paramagnetic resonance (EPR) studies of spin-labelled reagents attached to $\beta 93$ (McConnell et al., 1969). The EPR spectrum of liganded haemoglobin shows evidence for a conformational equilibrium between two orientations of the spin-label relative to the protein. The EPR spectra of haemoglobin liganded with carbon monoxide, azide, cyanide, oxygen, water and fluoride all show this conformational equilibrium but have small differences between their spectra suggesting structural differences in the liganded forms linked to the spin state of the iron atoms. The EPR spectrum of deoxyhaemoglobin, however, shows only one orientation of the spin-label corresponding to one of the orientations in liganded haemoglobin. Moffat (1971a) has given a structural interpretation of these EPR spectra. From an X-ray study of methaemoglobin with the spin-label bound, the two orientations between which the spin-label is oscillating could be identified. One position is free in solution on the outside of the protein, the other displaces Tyr $145 \beta$ and the C-terminus of the $\beta$-chain. The EPR spectra show that there is a very small energy barrier between the two positions for the spin-label, which shows that Tyr $145 \beta$ is easily displaced and is itself in a state of conformational equilibrium between different positions. This delocalization of $\operatorname{Tyr} 145 \beta$ was indicated by the poor definition in this region of the electron density map of methaemoglobin (section 3.3). In deoxyhaemoglobin, where $\operatorname{Tyr} 145 \beta$ is stabilized in one position by its hydrogen bond to the carboxyl group of Val $98 \beta$, only one orientation of the spin-label is seen corresponding to the position free on the surface of the molecule.

The EPR spectrum differences seen between the low spin ferrous or ferric derivatives (carbonmonoxy, azide, cyanide, oxy) and the high spin derivatives (met below pH 7.0 and fluoromet) indicate, in the light of Moffat's interpretation, that in high spin derivatives Tyr $145 \beta$ is more localized than in the low spin derivatives. This is consistent with the X-ray results of Heidner et al. (1975), which show that in low spin carbonmonoxyhaemoglobin the Tyr $145 \beta$ is displaced more out of the tyrosine pocket relative to methaemoglobin because Cys $93 \beta$ has moved into its pocket.

Huestis and Raftery (1972a) have also demonstrated conformation differences in the vicinity of $\beta 93$. They have used a reagent labelled with ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ attached to $\beta 93$ and studied the difference in the NMR spectrum in liganded and unliganded haemoglobins. The ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ NMR spectrum consists of a single absorption whose chemical shift changes with ligation state. The NMR spectra show that the environment of the probe is similar for the ligands oxygen, carbon monoxide and cyanide, although small differences indicate that the structures are not identical. The deoxyhaemoglobin spectrum is quite different. The ${ }^{19} \mathrm{~F}$ NMR spectrum of aquomethaemoglobin shows significant differences from oxyhaemoglobin which may correlate with the differences seen between the structures of carbonmonoxy- and methaemoglobin in this region.

The differences in the UV circular dichroism spectra of oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin are due to changes in the environment of the haems and aromatic residues. From a
comparison of the circular dichroism (CD) difference spectra of normal haemoglobin and a chemically modified haemoglobin known not to change its quaternary structure on oxygenation, Simon and Cantor (1969) showed that one region of the spectrum, around 260 nm is chiefly sensitive to the state of the haems, and another region, around 285 nm is associated with the change of quaternary structure. Tyr C7(42) $\alpha$ whose environment changes considerably between oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin may contribute to the part associated with the quaternary structure change (Perutz et al., 1974a). In oxyhaemoglobin the side chain of the tyrosine makes several contacts with Arg C6(40) $\beta$ and is hydrogen bonded to the amide group of Asn G4(97) $\alpha$. In deoxyhaemoglobin it makes fewer contacts with the arginine and is hydrogen bonded to Asp G1(99)β. From a comparison of the CD spectrum of normal haemoglobin with that of Hb Hirose, in which $\operatorname{Trp} \mathrm{C} 3(37) \beta$ is replaced by Ser (Yanase et al., 1968), it has been shown that the region of the spectrum at 387 nm is mainly due to $\operatorname{Trp} 37 \beta$ (Perutz, personal communication).

Differences in the UV absorption spectrum between oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin are due to changed environments of the haems and aromatic residues. The UV spectra of oxy-, met- and cyanomethaemoglobin are similar, showing small differences for each ligand, but deoxyhaemoglobin has a quite different spectrum. The spectrum of liganded haemoglobin also varies with pH (Briehl and Hobbs, 1970). A tentative identification of the aromatic residues contributing to the change between the liganded and deoxyhaemoglobin spectra suggested $\operatorname{Trp} \operatorname{C3(37)} \beta$ and $\operatorname{Tyr} \operatorname{C7(42)\alpha }$ in the $\alpha_{1} \beta_{2}$ contact (Briehl and Hobbs, 1970). From a comparison of the spectra between normal haemoglobin and haemoglobin Hirose, it has now been shown that Trp C3(37) $\beta$ makes only a minor contribution to the difference spectrum (Perutz, personal communication).

NMR spectroscopy has been used to detect conformational differences between liganded and unliganded haemoglobin, probably the changed environment of aromatic residues in the $\alpha_{1} \beta_{2}$ contacts (Ho et al., 1970; Patel et al., 1970). ${ }^{13} \mathrm{C}$ NMR differences between oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin indicate that several lysines are immobilized in deoxyhaemoglobin. At physiological pH methaemoglobin seems to have ${ }^{13} \mathrm{C}$ NMR properties intermediate between those of oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin (Moon and Richards, 1972).

The rate of digestion of the $C$-terminal residues is greater for liganded haemoglobin than for deoxyhaemoglobin (Zito et al., 1964). This is to be expected from the three-dimensional structures which show the C-terminal residues of both $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains to be free in liganded haemoglobin and salt bridged in deoxyhaemoglobin.

All this evidence confirms the view that the structure in solution and in the crystal are the same.

\subsection*{3.6. Structural Comparison of Tertiary Structures of Isolated Subunits with Subunits in Haemoglobin}

In section 2.5 the following two conclusions were drawn from the comparison of the ligand binding properties of haemoglobin and free chains. Firstly, that association of free deoxy subunits into the deoxy tetramer forces them into a conformation in which they have lowered affinity for the first ligand. Secondly, that the last stage of binding the ligands oxygen, carbon monoxide or $n$-butyl isocyanide to haemoglobin is similar to binding these ligands to free chains. Now from a structural comparison of the tertiary structures of the subunits when free and when in the tetramer, one can hope to see the reason why binding the first ligand to haemoglobin is different from binding to free chains, whereas binding the last ligand to haemoglobin is similar.

Comparison of deoxyhaemoglobin and deoxy free chains. Crystallographic studies of the deoxy forms of two monomeric globins have been described in section 3.2. Whilst not having identical ligand binding properties to $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains they have similar high affinity and kinetic constants. Data for myoglobin was included in Tables 1 and 3 for comparison. There is a slightly greater difference in properties between myoglobin and $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains in the case of carbon monoxide binding (Brunori and Shuster, 1969; Brunori et al., 1966). In myoglobin and erythrocruorin, the deoxy form has the iron
atom positioned about $0.3 / 0.4 \AA$ from the plane of the porphyrin ring (Table 5). In contrast, in deoxyhaemoglobin subunits the distance of the iron atom from the porphyrin plane is greater, being about $0.6 \AA$ for the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains.

Spectroscopic studies of the haem environment have also shown differences between free deoxy subunits and those in the tetramer. The electronic absorption spectrum in the visible region and in the near-ultraviolet region known as the Soret band differs between isolated subunits and deoxyhaemoglobin. The spectral difference consists of a decrease in the extinction coefficient at 430 nm and a broadening of the Soret band in isolated subunits as compared to deoxyhaemoglobin (Benesch et al., 1964; Antonini et al., 1965a; Brunori et al., 1968b). Also the NMR spectrum of the paramagnetically shifted proton resonances in the downfield region for human deoxyhaemoglobin is different from the spectrum that would result from a superposition of the resonance spectra of the isolated $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains (Perutz et al., 1974a).

Perutz et al. (1974c) have correlated the electron absorption spectrum difference and the NMR spectral differences with structural differences in the region of the haem groups between deoxy free subunits and deoxy subunits in the tetramer. They have given an interpretation of the spectral changes between the tetramer and free subunits as due to lengthening of the iron-nitrogen bonds to the porphyrin ring and to the proximal histidine. This is consistent with the iron atom and the proximal histidine being further from the mean plane of the porphyrin in deoxyhaemoglobin than in monomeric globins but, as the porphyrins in these structures are probably domed or puckered, the positions of the pyrrole nitrogen atoms are not known accurately enough to determine bond lengths. Perutz et al. suggest that the lowered rate constant and lowered affinity of the first ligand to bind to haemoglobin compared to binding to free chains may be associated with the spectral changes and the position of the iron.

Comparison of "rapid" haemoglobin with deoxy free chains. Gibson (1959) showed that "rapid" haemoglobin, formed by flash photolysis of fully liganded haemoglobin, had an electronic absorption spectrum that differed from that of normal "slow" deoxyhaemoglobin. It is in fact that corresponding to free deoxy chains. In other words, the intersubunit contacts in "rapid" haemoglobin do not produce constraints on the subunits that either lower the rate constant or alter the absorption spectrum. The correlation of absorption spectrum with iron position proposed by Perutz et al. implies that the deoxy subunit in "rapid" haemoglobin has its iron atom in the normal position for a high spin ferrous iron atom in a free subunit.

Comparison of liganded haemoglobin and liganded free chains. Crystallographic studies of the liganded forms of myoglobin and erythrocuorin were described in section 3.2. In both monomeric globins, the met form has the iron atom positioned $0.3 / 0.4 \AA$ from the plane of the porphyrin (see Table 5), whilst in methaemoglobin the iron atom is positioned $0.1 / 0.2 \AA$ from the mean plane. The studies of erythrocruorin showed the iron atom to be in the plane of the porphyrin for the carbonmonoxy form and in carbonmonoxyhaemoglobin the iron atom is closer to the mean plane than in methaemoglobin. In all these structures, however, the iron-nitrogen bond lengths are not known accurately.

Spectroscopic studies of the haem environments have shown only small differences between liganded subunits and liganded tetramers, except in the case of the aquomet derivative. The electronic absorption spectrum of oxy- and carbonmonoxyhaemoglobin in the visible and Soret regions is the same as that of the isolated subunit spectra (Brunori et al., 1968b). No dependence on pH has been reported. On the other hand, a change in the electronic absorption spectrum has been observed on association of isolated met subunits into methaemoglobin. Although the spectrum of free met $\alpha$-chains is like that of the $\alpha_{2} \beta_{2}$ tetramer, that of the $\beta_{4}$ tetramer changes on association (Banerjee and Cassoly, 1969a).

The paramagnetically shifted NMR resonance of cyanoferric isolated chains have been compared with those of cyanoferric haemoglobin (Ogawa et al., $1972 \mathrm{a}, \mathrm{b}$ ). The comparison shows that the $\alpha^{+}(\mathrm{CN})$ and the $\beta^{+}(\mathrm{CN})$ spectra can be distinguished in the tetramer spectrum, although the association of subunits to tetramer has altered the
haem environments slightly. The tetramer spectrum alters with pH and changes in ionic strength much more than the spectra of free chains do, and the authors suggest that the pH dependence is due to the titration of a histidine in the $\alpha_{1} \beta_{2}$ contact region.

The proton NMR spectra of the ring current shifted resonances of carbonmonoxyhaemoglobin indicate that the tertiary structure of the haem pockets are not significantly affected by the association of carbonmonoxy subunits into the tetramer. The contributions of the spectra of the isolated subunits can be added to give a close approximation of the intact tetramer spectrum (Lindstrom et al., 1972b). A difference in the liganded tetramer spectrum with pH change or change in anion concentration is also found, and is interpreted as a change in conformation of valines E11 relative to the haem plane (Lindstrom and Ho, 1973).

So association of liganded $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-subunits into the tetramer, except in the case of aquomet subunits, is accompanied by only small changes in the haem environment as detected by spectral methods. The haem environments in the tetramer are altered slightly by pH changes and ionic strength in a way not seen in the isolated subunits. If these alterations affect the subunit affinity, then the last binding step to the tetramer cannot be exactly the same as binding to free chains. This point will be discussed again in section 4.

Implications for the origin of co-operativity. In section 2.5 it was seen from thermodynamic arguments that since the assembly of $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-subunits into the deoxy tetramer lowers the affinity of the subunits for the first ligand, the favourable subunit contacts must produce some conformation changes in the subunits that lower their ligand affinity. In addition, since the last step in ligand binding is very like that for free chains, the oxy arrangement of the subunits is not associated with these constraints. Cooperativity is associated with the non-uniform release of the constraints of the deoxyhaemoglobin structure with ligation of the subunits.

The association between the normal deoxyhaemoglobin absorption spectrum and the existence of co-operativity was suggested by Brunori et al. (1968b). They noted that abnormal deoxyhaemoglobins whose co-operativity and related conformational changes had been lost, had the spectrum of isolated deoxy chains rather than the normal spectrum. Perutz et al. (1974c) have now interpreted this characteristic absorption spectrum of deoxyhaemoglobin, which is correlated with low affinity for the first ligand, in structural terms. It is associated with the position of the iron atom further from the plane of the porphyrin ring than is normal for a high spin ferrous iron atom. The iron is held in position as a result of tertiary structure changes resulting from the exceptionally stable contacts between subunits made in the deoxyhaemoglobin tetramer. On the other hand, the spectra of normal deoxy free chains is associated with the normal position of the iron and high affinity, and this is the situation for the last binding step in oxygen, carbon monoxide or $n$-butyl isocyanide to normal haemoglobin. The structures are not known accurately enough, however, to provide a test of the proposed correlation between the iron-nitrogen bond lengths and the spectra.

The preceding discussion has shown that there is some understanding of the origin of the difference in affinity of normal haemoglobin for its first and last ligand. How the change in quaternary structure is brought about and the connection between it and the changing constraints on the subunits in the tetramer will be the subject of later discussions. Section 4 will describe the effect of $\mathbf{p H}$ and anions on the affinity and co-operativity of normal haemoglobin and section 5 will describe the properties of abnormal haemoglobins. These give information on the nature of the intermediate states, an understanding of which is required for an understanding of co-operativity. Before moving on to this discussion some brief comments on the properties of haemoglobin dimers will be made.

