The expressions for the dependence of oxygen affinity on pH and for the release of protons on oxygenation can be obtained from the general expressions discussed in section 2.6. Writing $\mathrm{H}^{+}$for the ligand $X$ and $h$ as its concentration, eqs. (2.25) and (2.28) become
$$\log p_{m h}=\log p_{m}+\frac{1}{4}\left(\log \phi_{0}(h)-\log \phi_{4}(h)\right),$$
where $p_{m}$ is the value at very high pH
and
$$\frac{\Delta \mathrm{H}^{+}}{4}=\frac{d \log p_{m h}}{d \log h}=-\frac{d \log p_{m h}}{d \mathrm{pH}} .$$

Wyman (1939) showed that the differential titration curve for oxygenation (Fig. 9a) could be accounted for by a model in which there were two oxygen-linked ionizing groups per subunit of haemoglobin, one accounting for the effect at acid pH and the other for the effect at alkaline pH . In this model it is assumed there is no interaction between ionizable groups, either within the same subunit or in different subunits, and that $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-subunits are equivalent. For non-interacting groups, eqs. (2.30) and (2.31) can be used. Writing the constants $Q_{i j}$ in terms of the ionization constants $\mathrm{K}_{i j}$ of the groups
$$Q_{0 j}=\frac{1}{\mathrm{~K}_{0 j}}=10^{\mathrm{p} K_{0 j}} ; \quad Q_{4 j}=\frac{1}{\mathrm{~K}_{4 j}}=10^{\mathrm{p} K_{4 j}}$$
then from (2.30), if $q$ is the number of ionizing groups contributing,
$$\log p_{m h}=\log p_{m}+\frac{1}{4} \sum_{j=1}^{q}\left(\log \left(1+\frac{h}{\mathrm{~K}_{0 j}}\right)-\log \left(1+\frac{h}{\mathrm{~K}_{4 j}}\right)\right)$$
and from (4.2) and (2.31)
$$\frac{d \log p_{m h}}{d \mathrm{pH}}=-\frac{\Delta H^{+}}{4}=-\frac{1}{4} \sum_{i=1}^{q} \Delta H_{j}^{+}$$
where
$$\begin{aligned}
\Delta H_{j}^{+} & =\frac{d}{d \log h}\left(\log \left(1+\frac{h}{\mathrm{~K}_{0 j}}\right)-\log \left(1+\frac{h}{\mathrm{~K}_{4 j}}\right)\right) \\
& =\frac{h}{\mathrm{~K}_{0 j}+h}-\frac{h}{\mathrm{~K}_{4 j}+h}
\end{aligned}$$

In Wyman's model $q=8$, and there are four identical pairs of two groups. This model fits the data with the acid Bohr group changing its pK from 5.25 to 5.75 on oxygenation and the alkaline Bohr group changing its pK from 7.81 to 6.80 .

It has been shown that the oxidation Bohr effect can be accounted for approximately by the same ionizing groups as those responsible for the oxygenation Bohr effect, when allowance is made for the water molecule ionization (Wyman and Ingalls, 1941). There is a small residual oxidation Bohr effect, not accounted for in this way, from one or more additional ionizing groups contributing in the pH region 6.4 to 7.4 (Antonini et al., 1964).

It has been shown more recently that the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-subunits have different ionizing groups contributing to the alkaline Bohr effect, but so far there is no evidence on the separate contributions of the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-subunits to the acid Bohr effect. A model in which the proton binding sites are essentially non-interacting accounts for the Bohr effect of normal haemoglobin. This point will be discussed further in section 7 , in the light of later models of haemoglobin function.

\subsection*{4.1.2. Identification of ionizing groups contributing to the Bohr effect}

Experiments to identify groups contributing to the Bohr effect have involved modified haemoglobins whose Bohr effects are altered. These haemoglobins may have abnormal Bohr effects for either or both of two reasons. Firstly, one of the ionizing groups contributing to the Bohr effect may have been removed. Alternatively, the modification may have altered the $\mathbf{p K}$ 's of the normal groups. Identification of Bohr groups therefore requires a structural interpretation of the difference in $\mathbf{p K}$ of the group between normal oxy-and deoxyhaemoglobin as well as evidence that removal of the group changes the Bohr effect (Kilmartin and Rossi-Bernardi, 1973).

Two groups that change their $\mathbf{p K}$ between oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin in the alkaline pH range have now been clearly identified. One of these is histidine $\mathrm{HC} 3(146) \beta$ and the other is the $\alpha$-amino group of the $\alpha$-chains, valine $1 \alpha$.

Histidine $H C 3(146) \beta$ was suggested as a possible ionizing group contributing to the Bohr effect from the results of a low resolution X-ray study of NES haemoglobin (Perutz et al., 1969). NES haemoglobin is the derivative formed by blocking the reactive sulphydryl groups, cysteine $93 \beta$, with N-ethylmaleimide and it had previously been shown to have a reduced Bohr effect (Riggs, 1961; Benesch and Benesch, 1961, 1962). The electron density difference map of NES haemoglobin showed the NES bound to the cysteine and structural changes in the vicinity of the C-terminal His $146 \beta$ which was displaced from its normal position. Later, the structure of deoxyhaemoglobin determined from the high resolution maps of horse and human haemoglobin (Bolton and Perutz, 1970; Muirhead and Greer, 1970; Arnone et al., 1975) showed the presence of a salt bridge between the imidazole group of His $146 \beta$ and the carboxyl group of Asp $94 \beta$ which raises the pK of the imidazole group. In the structure determined from the high resolution map of horse methaemoglobin (Perutz et al., 1968b), His $146 \beta$ is free and would have a normal $\mathbf{p} \boldsymbol{K}$. The contribution of this salt bridge to the Bohr effect was demonstrated by removal of His $146 \beta$ by enzymatic modification, when the expected reduction in the alkaline Bohr effect was found (Kilmartin and Wootton, 1970). An X-ray study of des(His) showed that this modification had produced no change in tertiary structure other than the removal of the histidine (Perutz and TenEyck, 1971). The exact $\mathbf{p} \boldsymbol{K}$ values of His $146 \beta$ in deoxy-and carbonmonoxyhaemoglobin have now been measured from the proton NMR spectrum of normal haemoglobin at different pH values, the resonance due to His $146 \beta$ having been identified by comparison of the NMR spectra of normal and des(His). The experimental results could be accounted for if His $146 \beta$ has a pK of 7.2 in carbonmonoxyhaemoglobin and 8.1 in deoxyhaemoglobin at $25^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ (Kilmartin et al., 1973b).

The $\alpha$-amino group of Valine $1 \alpha$ has been shown by experiments on chemically modified haemoglobin (Kilmartin and Rossi-Bernardi, 1969, 1971) to contribute to the alkaline Bohr effect. The $\alpha$-amino groups of the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains were reacted with cyanate to give carbamylated amino groups which are unable to ionize in the normal pH range. It was found that if the $\beta$-chains only were carbamylated the Bohr effect was normal, but if the $\alpha$-chains are carbamylated the alkaline Bohr effect is reduced by $25 \%$ at pH 7.4 . Since X-ray analysis of the crystals of the modified haemoglobins showed no evidence of large structural changes in either the oxy or deoxy forms it was concluded that the reduced Bohr effect was the consequence of the blocking of one of the Bohr groups. An estimate of the $\mathbf{p K}$ change of the group from 7.3 in oxyhaemoglobin to 7.7 in deoxyhaemoglobin was obtained by subtracting the differential titration curve of carbamylated haemoglobin from that of normal haemoglobin. This procedure is valid provided there is negligible interaction between the normal ionizing groups.

The recently determined $2.5 \AA$ resolution Fourier map of human deoxyhaemoglobin (Arnone et al., 1975) does not provide a simple explanation of a raised pK of the $\alpha$-amino group of the $\alpha$-chains. In lower resolution maps, $2.8 \AA$ for horse deoxyhaemoglobin (Bolton and Perutz, 1970) and $3.5 \AA$ for human deoxyhaemoglobin (Muirhead and Greer, 1970), a salt bridge between the C-terminal carboxyl group of one $\alpha$-chain and the $\alpha$-amino group of the opposite $\alpha$-chain seemed possible, but this is not confirmed by the later map. The two groups are separated by $5 \AA$, and there may be a water molecule bound between them. There is a cluster of charged groups in the vicinity of the $\alpha$-amino group, illustrated in Fig. 7, which may have some effect on its pK. Thus it is unclear whether the contribution of the $\alpha$-amino group to the Bohr effect comes from a raising of its $\mathbf{p K}$ in the deoxy structure, perhaps due to a weak interaction through a water molecule with this cluster of charges or from a lowering of its pK in the oxy structure due to the proximity of the positively charged side chains of Arg $141 \alpha$. The involvement of an $\alpha$-amino group having an abnormally low pK in oxyhaemoglobin was suggested by Tanford and Nozaki (1966). Also, a direct measurement of the $\mathbf{p K}$ of the $\alpha$-amino group of the $\alpha$-chain in carbonmonoxyhaemoglobin gave a value of 6.72 (Hill and Davis, 1967), which is about one pH unit lower than the normal value to be expected for such a group. The suggested explanation for this low value was the proximity of positively charged group.

The remainder of the alkaline Bohr effect has no firm structural interpretation. The possibility of His G19(122) $\alpha$ being a Bohr group has been suggested (Perutz, 1970), and the interaction of bound chloride ions with certain residues in deoxyhaemoglobin leading to a change in their $\mathbf{p K}$ values is another possibility (Kilmartin and RossiBernardi, 1973). Table 10 shows the contribution to the total Bohr effect of the tetramer made by the identified groups just described. Using a model in which there is negligible interaction between different ionizing groups, the remainder of the Bohr effect could arise from one pair of ionizing groups with the pK change shown in the table, or several pairs of groups with smaller pK differences (Kilmartin et al., 1973b).

