Kinetic studies of the release of protons with ligand uptake have shown that for carbon monoxide binding there is a linear relationship between the number of protons released and the number of carbon monoxide molecules bound. Antonini et al. (1965b) have demonstrated this in the pH range 7.0 to 7.8 , and Gray (1970), Gray and Gibson (1971a) and Olson and Gibson (1973b) confirm this result. The linear relationship is not seen, however, in the case of binding $n$-butyl isocyanide (nBIC) to haemoglobin. This ligand has been shown to bind more rapidly to the $\beta$-chains than to the $\alpha$-chains of deoxyhaemoglobin (Olson and Gibson, 1972a), in contrast to the binding of carbon
monoxide which binds with equal rates to $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains (Gray and Gibson, 1971a). Heterogeneity in binding other isocyanides has also been found (Brunori et al., 1972). Olson and Gibson (1973a) have found that both proton release and n -BIC binding are biphasic, with $20 \%$ of the protons being released with the faster phase of $n$-BIC uptake and $80 \%$ with the slower phase, showing that with this ligand less protons are associated with ligating $\beta$-chains than with ligating $\alpha$-chains.

The kinetics of the last step in ligand binding and the first step in ligand dissociation show that proton release in the last ligation step is smaller than the average per ligation step. For the ligand n -BIC, the kinetic constants of the last n -BIC molecule to bind to haemoglobin and for the first n-BIC molecule to leave fully liganded haemoglobin show very little pH variation for either the $\alpha$ - or the $\beta$-chains (Olson and Gibson, 1971). Proton release with this ligand therefore seems to be complete by the stage when three ligands are bound to haemoglobin. For oxygen binding, however, there is some pH dependence of the rate constants for dissociation of the first oxygen molecule from fully oxygenated haemoglobin (see Table 12). There is a factor of about 2.5 between the "off" constant at pH 6.0 and pH 9.0 , it being larger at lower pH . Olson et al. (1971) have measured the separate constants within the tetramer for the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains and the $\alpha$-chains appear to have slightly more pH variation than the $\beta$ 's. If the fourth "on" constants for oxygenation do not vary with pH in the same way as the "off" constants, then the affinity for the fourth oxygen to bind to haemoglobin will have significant pH variation. It would correspond to a proton release of about a third of the average number of protons per subunit.

