\subsection*{4.1.4. The binding of protons to partially oxidized haemoglobin}

The shape of the oxidation-reduction equilibrium curves shows a clear variation with pH and non-linearity of proton release with percentage oxidation is observed (Brunori
et al., 1965). There is a decrease in $n$ with decreasing pH , as illustrated in Fig. 13, and the lag in proton release is more noticeable at lower pH than at pH 8.0 . Brunori et al. (1968a) have suggested that the variation in $n$ with pH is due to the heterogeneity between the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains being more marked at low pH than at high pH (see section 3.7).

Heterogeneity between the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains in the oxidation of normal haemoglobin has been observed (MacQuarrie and Gibson, 1971) and at partial oxidation there are less oxidized $\beta$-chains than oxidized $\alpha$-chains. This effect is observed at both pH 6.0 and pH 8.7 and therefore does not seem to be connected with the change in $n$ values between these two pH (Fig. 13). Also the fact that the proportion of oxidized $\alpha$-chains to that of oxidized $\beta$-chains is the same at the two pH values, does not parallel the relative oxidation-reduction potentials of the free $\beta_{4^{-}}$and $\alpha$-subunits at these pH values. Banerjee and Cassoly (1969a) find that $\beta_{4}$ has a higher half-reduction potential than $\alpha$-chains at low pH but an equal half-reduction potential to that of $\alpha$-chains at pH 8.0 . The explanation of the difference in behaviour in oxidation and oxygenation is therefore not simply the greater heterogeneity between the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains in oxidation as opposed to oxygenation.

\subsection*{4.2. The Interaction of Haemoglobin with Organic Phosphates and Other Salts}

The oxygen affinity of haemoglobin is influenced by the presence of salts (Antonini et al., 1962) and the presence of organic phosphates, in particular 2,3-diphosphoglycerate (DPG) and inositol hexaphosphate (IHP) (Benesch and Benesch, 1967; Chanutin and Curnish, 1967). Figure 10a illustrates the dependence of the oxygen equilibrium curve on the presence of NaCl , and the addition of DPG and IHP. The data are taken from Tyuma et al. (1973a) and Imai (1974) and the Adair constants of the equilibrium curves are given in Table 14. The effect on the oxygen equilibrium shows that deoxyhaemoglobin has a higher affinity for salts and organic phosphates than has oxyhaemoglobin.

\subsection*{4.2.1. Direct measurement of the binding of organic phosphate and salts}

2,3-Diphosphoglycerate binding to deoxyhaemoglobin has been shown to have a stoichiometry of one mole per mole tetramer in the presence of 0.1 M NaCl and at haemoglobin concentrations of about $10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}$. The association constant for DPG binding to deoxyhaemoglobin is pH dependent and is about $10^{5} \mathrm{~m}^{-1}$. At higher NaCl concentrations, the binding of DPG to deoxyhaemoglobin is decreased, suggesting competition between NaCl and DPG for the same binding site. At low ionic strength the binding of DPG to deoxyhaemoglobin is increased and more than one mole per mole tetramer may be bound. The value of the association constant for DPG binding at several pH's is shown in Table 13a (Benesch et al., 1969; Benesch et al., 1971). Under conditions when the haemoglobin concentration is as low as $10^{-4} \mathrm{~m}$, binding to oxyhaemoglobin cannot be detected directly. However, both oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin show measurable binding of DPG in conditions corresponding to those in the red cell (Berger et al., 1973). The association constants obtained by Berger et al. are shown in Table 13b for comparison with those obtained at lower haemoglobin concentrations.

Inositol hexaphosphate has been shown to have an association constant for oxyhaemoglobin of about $10^{6} \mathrm{~m}^{-1}$ at pH 7.0 in 0.11 m NaCl . The stoichiometry of binding is one mole IHP per mole haemoglobin (Gray and Gibson, 1971b). A very similar association constant is found for the binding of IHP to methaemoglobin at pH 6.0 in 0.2 m bis-tris buffer, where the stoichiometry is also one mole IHP per mole tetramer (Perutz et al., 1974b). The binding of IHP to deoxyhaemoglobin is too great for the association constant to be measured.

Sodium chloride binding to oxy-, carbonmonoxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin has been studied by NMR quadrupole relaxation methods (Chiancone et al., 1972). Chloride binds to many sites and the high affinity binding sites have been shown to be oxygen linked, with deoxyhaemoglobin binding more at these sites than oxyhaemoglobin. Chloride and organic phosphates compete for the same high affinity binding site.

DPG binding to isolated subunits has been investigated by Benesch et al. (1968).

