\subsection*{4.2.4. The binding of organic phosphates to partially oxygenated haemoglobin}

The change of shape of the oxygen equilibrium curve in the presence of organic phosphates is illustrated by the data of Tyuma et al. (1973a) (Fig. 10 a,b and Table 14). A change of shape with type of salt and to a lesser extent with change in DPG concentration is seen. In the case of Fig. 10b, the change of shape is small and the value of Hill's constant hardly changes with DPG concentration, but differences show up in the Adair constants in Table 14. As discussed in section 2.6, this change of shape implies non-uniform release of bound anions and organic phosphates with oxygenation.

Very little bound chloride or DPG is released from haemoglobin in the final ligation step with oxygen as shown by the almost unaltered values of $A_{4}^{\prime}$ in the presence of 0.1 m NaCl and DPG. The constancy of $A_{4}^{\prime}$ in these conditions is consistent with kinetic findings. Gibson (1970) has shown that the kinetic constants for the last step in oxygenation are the same in low ionic strength buffer as in the presence of phosphate. Olson and Gibson (1971) have shown that the kinetic constants for the last step in n-BIC binding are not affected by DPG. Salhany et al. (1972) have shown that the rate of oxygen dissociation from fully liganded haemoglobin is not affected by DPG. All the results indicate that in the presence of DPG, $\mathrm{Hb}\left(\mathrm{O}_{2}\right)_{3}$ has the oxy quaternary structure as it also has in the absence of DPG.

The difference in $A_{4}^{\prime}$ caused by the presence of IHP combined with the evidence that IHP does not bind to $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-monomers shows that some IHP is released from haemoglobin in the final step of oxygenation. The change in $A_{4}^{\prime}$ with IHP is consistent with kinetic findings. IHP affects the kinetic constants of the last binding step for carbon monoxide binding (Gray and Gibson, 1971b).

The difference in $A_{1}^{\prime}$ when organic phosphates are present indicate that organic phosphates and salts are released from haemoglobin in the first oxygenation step. Kinetic findings are again consistent with the equilibrium results. Gibson (1970) showed the kinetic constants for the first oxygenation step to be different in the presence and absence of phosphates, the greatest difference being in the "off" constant. Gray and Gibson (1971a, b) have found a decrease in the rate of ligand uptake in the presence of IHP.

From the change in $A_{1}^{\prime}$ with type of organic phosphate, estimates can be made of the change in the free energy of binding the first ligand, RT $\ln A_{1}^{\prime}$, produced by bound salt.

The presence of 0.1 m NaCl increases the free energy of ligand binding by 0.65 kcal per mole haem over its value in low ionic strength buffer. The presence of 2 mm DPG or IHP in addition to 0.1 m NaCl further increases the free energy of ligand binding by 0.5 and 0.75 kcal per mole haem, respectively. Structural changes that could be associated with the differences in $A_{1}^{\prime}$ in the presence and absence of salts and organic phosphates have been suggested by Arnone and Perutz (1974) (section 4.2.3.). Small tertiary structure changes in the $\beta$-subunits are seen when DPG and IHP are bound to deoxyhaemoglobin, suggesting that the effect of $A_{1}^{\prime}$ may result from a changed affinity of the $\beta$-subunit for the first ligand. Olson and Gibson (1972a, 1973a) and Gray and Gibson (1971a) have reported, however, that the $\alpha$-chains are more affected by DPG and IHP than the $\beta$-chains in regard to binding the first ligand.

The release of DPG as a function of ligand saturation has been studied by Huestis and Raftery (1972c) using ${ }^{31} \mathrm{P}$ NMR spectroscopy, and their results show that the fraction of DPG released is less than the fraction of ligand bound at intermediate saturation. Tyuma et al. (1973a) show that their equilibrium results imply a lag in DPG release behind oxygen saturation. Kinetic studies also show that DPG release lags behind ligand uptake. MacQuarrie and Gibson (1972) have used a fluorescent analogue of DPG and followed its release with carbon monoxide uptake.

Release of DPG is therefore not equally linked to each of the four ligation steps. Since no DPG release is associated with the last ligation step which is probably taking place in the oxy quaternary structure, DPG has been released to its full extent by the time this quaternary structure has formed. This conclusion is to be expected from structural considerations since DPG and IHP cannot bind in exactly the same sites in deoxy and in liganded haemoglobin.

