\subsection*{5.1.2. The effect of ionic strength changes and the presence of organic phosphates on the affinity and co-operativity}

High affinity haemoglobins. In common with the other high affinity non-cooperative haemoglobins, des(His.Tyr) in low ionic strength buffer has a deoxy absorption spectrum like free chains which is characteristic of deoxyhaemoglobins in the oxy quaternary structure. The same haemoglobin crystallizes in the deoxy quaternary structure (Perutz and TenEyck, 1971). So deoxy des(His.Tyr) appears to be in either quaternary structure depending on solution conditions. It has also been shown to regain co-operativity and to regain the deoxy absorption spectrum normally associated with co-operative haemoglobins, when IHP is present (Bonaventura et al., 1972).

There are other high affinity, normally non-cooperative haemoglobins, whose properties are altered by change in ionic strength, in particular by the presence of IHP. Hb Bethesda and Hb Rainier become more co-operative and have lowered affinity in the presence of DPG (Hayashi and Stamatoyannopoulos, 1972). Hb Bethesda is fast reacting towards ligand and has a chain-like absorption spectrum in the absence of IHP, but is slowly reacting and has an absorption spectrum like deoxyhaemoglobin on the addition of IHP (Olson and Gibson, 1972b). Also the haemoglobins NES des(Arg), des(Arg.Tyr) (Kilmartin et al., 1974) and Hb Kempsey (Bunn et al., 1974) have lowered affinity and increased co-operativity in the presence of DPG and IHP. Table 18 shows the effect on $\log p_{50}$ and $n$ that is produced by adding DPG or IHP to these and other haemoglobins. The value of $\log p_{50}$ in stripped conditions is given, and $\Delta \log p_{50}$ produced by adding DPG or IHP. By equation (2.19), in section 2.6.2, $\Delta \log p_{m}$ the
change in $\log p_{m}$ in the presence of DPG is
$$\begin{aligned}
\Delta \log p_{m} & =\log p_{m, \mathrm{dpg}}-\log p_{m, 0} \\
& =\frac{1}{4}\left[\log \left(1+B_{0}[\mathrm{DPG}]\right)-\log \left(1+B_{4}[\mathrm{DPG}]\right)\right]
\end{aligned}$$
where $\boldsymbol{B}_{\mathbf{0}}$ and $\boldsymbol{B}_{4}$ are the association constants for DPG binding to deoxy and fully liganded haemoglobin. If the association constants $\boldsymbol{B}_{0}$ and $\boldsymbol{B}_{4}$ are unaltered by modifications to the protein, $\Delta \log p_{m}$ would be the same for abnormal haemoglobins in the presence of the same concentration of DPG. Only for Hb Chesapeake, des(Arg), NES Hb and Hb Hiroshima is this approximately true (see Table 18).

Perutz et al. (1974a) discuss evidence that the restoration of co-operativity by IHP for the haemoglobins NES des(Arg), des(Arg.Tyr) and Hb Kempsey is correlated with the restored ability of the deoxy forms to take up the deoxy quaternary structure. There is evidence from changes in the spectra from aromatic residues in the $\alpha_{1} \beta_{2}$ interface and from the reactivity of the - SH groups of $\beta 93$, that the deoxy forms of these haemoglobins have the normal deoxy quaternary arrangement in the presence of IHP whereas they have the oxy quaternary arrangement in its absence. Also in these and other high affinity haemoglobins, the absorption spectrum from the deoxy haem groups becomes like that of normal deoxyhaemoglobin when co-operativity is restored in the presence of organic phosphates whereas it was like that of free deoxy chains in their absence. Organic phosphates can therefore stabilize abnormal haemoglobins in the deoxy quaternary structure, and with the restoration of this structure with its associated absorption spectrum, co-operativity is restored. This conclusion will appear later as an important factor in suggesting a model of haemoglobin function.

Haemoglobins with low values of $n$ and fairly high affinity in the absence of organic phosphates such as des(Arg) and Hb Chesapeake, NES Hb and Hb Hiroshima have their $\log p_{50}$ values increased and their co-operativity increased in the presence of DPG and IHP (see Table 18). Deoxy des(Arg) haemoglobin also shows evidence of both the deoxy and oxy quaternary structures being present together in solution in some conditions. The deoxy form of human des(Arg) crystallizes isomorphously with normal human deoxy haemoglobin. The deoxy form of horse des(Arg), however, crystallizes isomorphously with normal horse oxyhaemoglobin, in spite of the fact that the functional properties of the two species are very similar. This suggests that in solution, the structure of des(Arg) of both species is a mixture of the two quaternary structures, and that the crystal form obtained is determined by the relative solubilities of the two quaternary structures for each species. The solubility of human deoxyhaemoglobin is less than that of human oxy, whereas the solubility of horse deoxyhaemoglobin is greater than that of horse oxy (Perutz and TenEyck, 1971).

Haemoglobin Kansas with low value of $n$ and low affinity shows no noticeable change in $n$ in the presence of DPG at pH 7.0 (Gibson et al., 1973). The effect of DPG on the oxygen affinity of Hb Kansas is much smaller than its affect on HbA . Ogawa et al. (1972c) present NMR evidence that in the presence of organic phosphates Hb Kansas has its oxygenated form in the deoxy quaternary structure.

\subsection*{5.1.3. The Bohr effects}

The Bohr effects included in Table 15 are estimated as a percentage of the normal value of ( $\Delta \log p_{50} / \Delta \mathrm{pH}$ ) between pH 7.0 and pH 8.0 . For the significantly co-operative haemoglobins (from $\alpha_{2}^{c} \beta_{2}$ to Hb Chesapeake in Table 15) the Bohr effect is $100 \%$ of the normal value except in those cases where a known Bohr group (section 4.1.2) has been perturbed or removed. For example, des(His), NES Hb and Hb Hiroshima all have the His $146 \beta$-Asp $94 \beta$ salt bridge missing, and cyanate-blocked haemoglobin has the $\alpha$-amino group of the $\alpha$-chains blocked. The non-cooperative haemoglobins which have the quaternary structure of normal oxyhaemoglobin and do not change it whatever the state of ligation, all have reduced or negligible Bohr effects. The significance of the Bohr effects of abnormal haemoglobins will be discussed further in section 7 in the light of the model of haemoglobin function. The Bohr effects of des(Arg), NES des(Arg), des(Arg.Tyr), Hb Kempsey and des(His.Tyr) are all increased
in the presence of IHP (Table 18) and the significance of this will also be discussed in section 7.

\subsection*{5.2. The M Mutants and the Mixed-valency Hybrids}

The M mutants are the class of haemoglobins in which the iron atoms of one type of chain are permanently oxidized as a result of the replacement of a haem contact residue. Related to the M mutants are the artificially produced mixed-valency hybrids, which are obtained by reassembling free $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains after one type of chain has been oxidized (Banerjee and Cassoly, 1969b; Haber and Koshland, 1969; Brunori et al., 1970). The mixed-valency hybrids are possible analogues of the intermediate structures formed during the ligation of normal haemoglobin and as such are particularly interesting.

Data on the oxygen equilibrium properties of M mutants and mixed-valency hybrids are shown in Table 19, where it can be seen that their $\log p_{50}$ values lie in the range between $-\log A_{1}^{\prime}$ for normal haemoglobin and $\log p_{50}$ of the free ferrous $\alpha$-or $\beta$-chain.

When only two chains can bind oxygen, the analogous expression to eq. (5.1) for the relation between $\log p_{m}$ and $\log p_{s}$ is
$$\log p_{m}=\log p_{s}+\frac{1}{2} \log \frac{K_{M 0}}{K_{M 2}}$$
where $p_{s}$ denotes the median ligand activity of the free ferrous subunit, and $K_{M 0}$ and $K_{M 2}$ are the association constants of subunits to tetramers when there are 0 or 2 oxygen molecules bound to the ferrous subunits.

The change in oxygen affinity produced by the binding of organic phosphates is given by the analogous equation to (5.2)
$$\begin{aligned}
\Delta \log p_{m} & =\log p_{m, D P G}-\log p_{m, 0} \\
& =\frac{1}{2}\left[\log \left(1+B_{M 0}[\mathrm{DPG}]\right)-\log \left(1+B_{M 2}[\mathrm{DPG}]\right)\right]
\end{aligned}$$
where $\boldsymbol{B}_{\mathbf{M} \mathbf{0}}$ and $\boldsymbol{B}_{\mathbf{M 2}}$ denote the association constants for organic phosphate to the abnormal haemoglobin with 0 and 2 oxygen molecules bound to the normal ferrous subunits. Table 20 shows the change in oxygen affinity produced by the presence of organic phosphates for those M mutants and hybrids for which this has been determined.

The low affinity, non-cooperative haemoglobins M Iwate and M Boston, both of which have normal $\beta$-chains, have oxygen affinities very similar to that of normal haemoglobin for its first ligand (Table 19). The structures of these haemoglobins have been studied by X-ray techniques. Greer (1971b) determined the structure of fully reduced Hb Iwate (i.e. the structure with the normal $\beta$-chains and the abnormal met $\alpha$-chains both reduced). This structure had the same quaternary arrangement of subunits as in normal deoxyhaemoglobin, and it could be oxidized in the crystals without them breaking up, showing that met Hb Iwate could exist in the deoxy quaternary structure. Two other forms of Hb Iwate have now been crystallized (Perutz and Frier, personal communication). One is the form of deoxy Hb Iwate in which the abnormal $\alpha$-chains are still in the met form. Its crystals differ from those of the fully reduced form and the quaternary structure is still unknown, although the unit cell dimensions suggest the deoxy quaternary structure. The other form that has been crystallized is carbonmonoxy Hb Iwate in which the $\alpha$-chains are still met and the normal $\beta$-chains combined with carbon monoxide. These crystals are similar to those of normal carbonmonoxyhaemoglobin. Hb Iwate therefore has the deoxy quaternary structure if the normal $\beta$-chains are deoxy or met but the oxy quaternary structure if they are combined with carbon monoxide. Slightly different properties have been found for Hb Boston which crystallizes in the normal deoxy form when deoxygenated but in a form isomorphous with carbonmonoxy Hb Iwate when its normal $\beta$-chains are met (Pulsinelli et al., 1973).

The oxygen affinity of Hb Iwate is altered very little by the presence of DPG (Table 20), showing that the association constants for DPG of its oxy and deoxy forms are very alike.

