Comparison of model predictions and experiments on conformation changes as a function of ligand saturation. If a conformational probe, such as those described in section 3.5, detects changes in quaternary structure only, the percentage change of the probe will not be a linear function of ligand saturation. If the probe detects changes in tertiary structure only, independently of whether the subunit is in $R$ or $T$, the percentage change of the probe will be an exactly linear function of ligand saturation. The former conformation change at the probe is described as being quaternary linked, the latter as tertiary linked in both $R$ and $T$, and there are other possibilities such as being quaternary linked and also tertiary linked in $T$.

Figure 17 illustrates the percentage of molecules in the various intermediate states as a function of ligand saturation $\bar{Y}$ for two sets of parameters, one with $L c^{2}=10$ (a) and the other with $L c^{2}=1 / 10(b)$. When $L c^{2}=1 / 10$ the concentration of $R_{3}$ is greater than that of $T_{1}$ for quite low fractional saturations, whereas for $L c^{2}=10$ the concentration of $T_{1}$ remains higher than that of $R_{3}$ until quite high fractional saturation. In both cases the concentrations of $T_{2}, T_{3}, T_{4}, R_{0}, R_{1}, R_{2}$ are always small. From such a figure the percentage change of a probe which is sensitive to structural changes at specified stages in ligation can be predicted. For example, if the probe is only sensitive to the quaternary structure change its percentage change with fractional saturation $\bar{Y}$ will follow the curve of total $R$ (or total $T$ ), and in the two cases illustrated the deviation from being a linear function is quite small. It is therefore difficult experimentally to distinguish quaternary linkage from tertiary linkage in a co-operative system.

Local conformation changes in the vicinity of the -SH group of $\beta 93$ have been studied by several investigators. In equilibrium studies Ogawa and McConnell (1967) found a linear relationship between conformation change at $\beta 93$ and ligand saturation but Huestis and Raftery (1972b, d, 1973) found that the conformation change lagged behind ligand saturation. In kinetic studies on the increase in rate of reaction of the -SH group with ligand uptake Antonini and Brunori (1969) found a linear relationship, but in a more recent study Gibson (1973b) finds that the increase in reaction rate lagged behind ligand uptake. Gibson's result suggests that the major change in - SH reactivity occurs when the quaternary structure changes. As discussed in section 3.5, conformation changes in the vicinity of the - SH group result from the transition from high to low spin of the iron atom as well as from the quaternary structure change. Conformation changes in the $\alpha_{1} \beta_{2}$ interface, which might structurally be expected to reflect the quaternary structure change, have been studied by Simon and Cantor (1969) and Imai and Yonetani (1973). The former authors found that the conformation change was proportional to ligand saturation and the latter authors that it lagged behind. Conformation changes in the vicinity of the haem group have been studied by Asakura (1972) who found that the conformation change lagged behind ligand saturation.

Other indicators of conformation change are the release of protons and organic phosphates, and experiments investigating these will be discussed in more detail later.

