\subsection*{7.7. The Interaction with Organic Phosphates}

The role of DPG and IHP as simple allosteric effectors, binding more strongly to $T$ than to $\boldsymbol{R}$, has already been considered in previous sections. The possibility has to be considered, however, that DPG and IHP bind slightly differently to the $T$ and $R$ states, depending on the state of ligation of the subunits within $T$ and $R$. The complete specification of the model for haemoglobin requires a knowledge of the binding of organic phosphates to the intermediate states.

Experimental evidence on organic phosphate binding. Many results confirm the view that organic phosphates are mainly released when the quaternary structure changes.

Release of DPG as a function of ligand saturation. As mentioned in section 4.2, Huestis and Raftery (1972c) observed a lag in fractional release of DPG as a function of fractional saturation with ligand. A lag in DPG release is expected if the binding of DPG is quaternary linked, and if $L c^{2}>1$ the fraction of DPG released will be less than $50 \%$ when the ligand saturation is $50 \%$. The experiments showed that the lag was greater at pH 6.5 than at pH 7.4 which is consistent with $L$ being greater at the lower pH . The authors, however, give an alternative interpretation of their results not in terms of the allosteric model.

When $L c^{2}>1$, Fig. 17 shows that the fractional release of DPG would be expected to be greater than $50 \%$ when the ligand saturation is $50 \%$, if DPG release is mainly linked to the quaternary structure change. Experiments that might have demonstrated this property of the allosteric model are those of Ogata and McConnell (1972) and Ogata et al. (1972) who used their spin-label technique to study the release of an analogue of DPG from two abnormal haemoglobins which have high affinity and therefore low expected values of $L$. They found, however, that for both Hb Chesapeake and Hb Kempsey the release of organic phosphate did not show this effect. These results are consistent with the allosteric model if in each case the affinity of one type of subunits in the $T$ state is almost equal to that in the $R$ state, so that combination of the haemoglobin with the first two ligands does not alter the allosteric equilibrium or release organic phosphate. Hb Chesapeake and Hb Kempsey have both been studied by NMR techniques and ligands bind preferentially to the $\alpha$-chains in Hb Chesapeake (Davis et al., 1971) to the $\beta$-chains in Hb Kempsey (Lindstrom et al., 1973). Since the
modifications alter $L$, two effects may contribute to the results of preferential binding experiments. Firstly, heterogeneity between $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains that is present even in normal haemoglobin may become apparent (see section 7.5) and secondly, the difference between the affinity of the $\alpha$-and $\beta$-chains may have been increased by the modification.

Kinetic studies of the release of DPG with ligand uptake. The results of MacQuarrie and Gibson (1972), mentioned in section 4.2.4, showed a kinetic lag between carbon monoxide uptake and DPG release in normal haemoglobin. This lag was greater at pH 6.0 than at pH 7.5 , which is consistent with $L$ being larger at the lower pH . The authors also studied abnormal haemoglobins that have increased affinity, including des(His), Hb Hiroshima, Hb Chesapeake, HbA treated with $p$-mercuribenzoate, all of which showed less lag than normal HbA , consistent with their having lower values of $L$ and changing quaternary structure earlier in the course of ligation. The increased lag in proton release behind ligand uptake found in the presence of organic phosphates (see section 4.2.5) is consistent with the release of organic phosphates (and the extra protons associated with their binding to deoxyhaemoglobin) being mainly linked to the quaternary structure change.

Evidence from the change in shape of oxygen equilibrium curves in the presence of chloride and organic phosphates. If organic phosphate binding is only quaternary linked, the allosteric model predicts a variation in $n$ value with type of salt and with salt concentration, although if $L$ is such that $n$ is near its maximum there will be only a small variation in $n$ (see Fig. 16). Also $K_{T}$ and $K_{R}$ are invariant and when co-operativity is high $A_{1}^{\prime}$ is effectively $1 / K_{T}$ and $A_{4}^{\prime}$ is effectively $1 / K_{R}$. But if organic phosphate binding depends on the number of ligated subunits in the $T$ or $R$ states, $A_{1}^{\prime}$ and $A_{4}^{\prime}$ will alter with type and concentration of organic phosphates.

The values of $A_{4}^{\prime}$ for oxygen equilibrium curves are almost the same in low ionic strength buffer and when chloride or DPG is present (Table 14). In the presence of IHP $A_{4}^{\prime}$ is smaller, but is consistent with the prediction of the allosteric model for a large value of $L$ when both the affinity and co-operativity are lower than normal (to the right-hand side of Fig. 16). The available data on $A_{4}^{\prime}$ are therefore consistent with a value of $K_{R}$ that varies by a factor of about 2 depending on the ionic strength of the solution.

The values of $A_{1}^{\prime}$ for oxygen equilibrium curves are not invariant with type and concentration of salts (see Table 14). The large change in $A_{\prime}^{\prime}$ resulting from the presence of chloride or organic phosphates shows that chloride and phosphates must be released on ligation of a subunit in the $T$ state (see the discussion in section 2.6.2). In low ionic strength buffer, organic phosphates do not bind with stoichiometry one mole per tetramer, and in these conditions they may be binding to many sites on the separate subunits.

In the presence of 0.1 m NaCl , organic phosphates bind with stoichiometry one mole per tetramer to a specific site between the $\beta$-chains in deoxyhaemoglobin and to an unknown site in oxyhaemoglobin (see section 4.2.3). The variation in $A_{1}^{\prime}$ with the presence of organic phosphates is smaller in these conditions and may be within experimental error. In the presence of IHP, $A_{1}^{\prime}$ decreases by a factor 3.5, and in the presence of DPG by a factor of 2 . If these changes are real, then to some extent IHP and DPG are released on ligation of a subunit in the $T$ structure. Structural changes at the $\beta$-haems that could be associated with the effect of organic phosphates on the ligand affinity in the $T$ state were described in section 4.2.3.

The implication of a dependence of organic phosphate binding on the state of ligation in the $T$ state in the presence of 0.1 m NaCl when there is one mole per tetramer bound to a specific site, is that there is interaction between subunits within one quaternary structure in respect of ligand binding. From structural considerations it is reasonable that the binding constant of DPG to the $T$ state would be affected by ligation of the $\beta$-chains only. In this case, by analogy with equations (2.19) in section 2.6.2,
$$K_{T \beta 1}=K_{T \beta} \times \frac{\left(1+B_{0}[\mathrm{DPG}]\right)}{\left(1+B_{\beta 1}[\mathrm{DPG}]\right)}$$
$$K_{T \beta 2}=K_{T \beta} \times \frac{\left(1+B_{\beta 1}[\mathrm{DPG}]\right)}{\left(1+B_{\beta 2}[\mathrm{DPG}]\right)}$$
where $K_{T \beta}$ is the oxygen dissociation constant of the $\beta$-chains in the absence of DPG, and $K_{T \beta 1}$ and $K_{T \beta 2}$ are the constants for the first and second oxygen to bind to the $\beta$-chains when DPG is present. $\boldsymbol{B}_{0}, \boldsymbol{B}_{\beta 1}, \boldsymbol{B}_{\beta 2}$ denote the binding constants of DPG to the $T$ state when 0,1 , or 2 chains are oxygenated. In general $K_{T \beta 1}$ differs from $K_{T \beta 2}$, which is a case of interaction between subunits in the $T$ state. The structural reason for the interaction is that DPG or IHP is bound between two subunits. In the formulation of the allosteric model for proton binding (section 7.5) it was assumed that proton release in the $T$ state is the result of tertiary structure changes in one subunit only. However, if some of the protons associated with the pH -dependent intersubunit salt bridges were released by tertiary structure changes in either of the subunits to which the salt bridging residues belong, then direct interaction between the subunits would arise.

This emphasizes how little difference there is in structural terms between a model in which there is no direct interaction between subunits and one in which such interactions occur, and shows that direct interactions are very likely to occur to some extent. Nevertheless, the major difference in affinity for the first and last ligand to bind to haemoglobin would still result from the change in quaternary structure when many constraints on the subunits are removed together.

\section*{8. CONCLUSIONS}

The allosteric model, combined with the structural understanding of its parameters, has been shown to describe qualitatively many of the functional properties of haemoglobin. In this model, two quaternary conformations with different oxygen affinities exist in equilibrium at all stages of oxygenation. The low affinity conformation, $T$, has the quaternary structure of deoxyhaemoglobin, whereas the high affinity conformation, $R$, has the quaternary structure of oxyhaemoglobin. A subunit in the $R$ form has an oxygen affinity and an absorption spectrum like those of isolated subunits, whereas a subunit in the $T$ form has a lower oxygen affinity and an altered spectrum due to structural differences in the vicinity of the haem group. The bonds from the iron atom to the nitrogens of the haem group and of the haem-linked histidine are longer, with the iron atom lying further out of the plane of the haem group in a subunit in the $T$ state than in a free subunit. This tertiary structure is stabilized by the intersubunit contacts of the $T$ form, particularly by the salt bridges and hydrogen bonds formed by the last two residues at the C -termini of both the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-chains.

When the high spin ferrous iron atom of a deoxy subunit combines with a ligand, its radius changes as a consequence of its changed valency or spin state and it moves further into the plane of the porphyrin ring of the haem group accompanied by changes in tertiary structure of the subunit. In the $T$ state these tertiary structure changes destabilize the intersubunit contacts, decreasing the stability of the $T$ form relative to the $R$ form. When several ligands are bound, the $R$ form becomes more stable than the $T$ form. The movement of the iron atom, and hence the extent to which the $T$ state is destabilized, is greater if the iron atom is low spin ferrous or low spin ferric after it has combined with ligand, as in oxygenation, than if the iron atom is high spin ferric, as in oxidation to the aquomet form.

The altered oxygen affinities of many abnormal haemoglobins are understood, independently of the allosteric model of the intermediate states, in terms of the altered structures of either their oxy or deoxy forms. The differences in co-operativity among abnormal haemoglobins are qualitatively explained by the allosteric model in which the structural changes are seen as altering the relative stability of the $R$ and $T$ forms at all stages of oxygenation. This allosteric equilibrium is altered particularly by modifications to the C -terminal residues of either chain or to residues in the $\alpha_{1} \beta_{2}$ contact. In addition to their effect on the allosteric equilibrium, some modifications alter the affinity of the subunits in the T state and affect the $\alpha$ - and $\beta$-subunits unequally.

The dependence of oxygen affinity on pH is largely understood, again independently of the allosteric model, in terms of altered ionization constants of identified Bohr
groups in oxy- and deoxyhaemoglobin. The Bohr groups contributing to the acid Bohr effect and to part of the alkaline Bohr effect are not identified yet. The dependence of co-operativity on pH can be described by the allosteric model. In the alkaline pH range, the equilibrium between the $R$ and $T$ forms of deoxyhaemoglobin is influenced towards $T$ by lower pH , whereas the equilibrium for fully oxygenated haemoglobin is nearly independent of $\mathbf{p H}$. The oxygen affinity of subunits in the $T$ state is lower at low $\mathbf{p H}$ because some $\mathbf{p H}$-dependent salt bridges are broken on oxygenation of subunits in the $T$ state, but the stage in oxygenation at which each of the ionizing groups is perturbed is not yet fully described.

The effect of organic phosphates on the oxygen equilibrium properties of normal, abnormal and hybrid haemoglobins is well described by the allosteric model, with organic phosphates influencing the allosteric equilibrium towards the $T$ form. The binding site for organic phosphates in deoxyhaemoglobin is established whereas that in oxyhaemoglobin is not yet known.

The allosteric model with structural evidence for changes in its parameters provides a framework in which many properties of haemoglobin can be described in a unified way. Detailed quantitative tests of the model are complicated by the number of parameters that can vary either if the conditions are changed or if the structure is modified. The most promising system for a quantitative test of some aspects of the model is provided by the artificial mixed-valency hybrids in which only two subunits can combine with oxygen while the protein structure is normal.

